history.content: The probability covered in MATH 55 would not be sufficient for EECS 126. I'd recommend taking/auditing STAT 134 this summer if you still choose to enroll. If you wish to do the bare minimum, you could self study the portions not covered in 55. That would be Poisson Processes, continuous distributions (Uniform, Exponential, Normal etc), Joint Distributions, conditional probabilities, Markov Chains and a couple other I may be missing. You could check the website for more. 55 should give you the background to self-study 70 pretty well.

children.subject: The rigor and pace is much higher however and a lack of good probability intuition of the same material might make it very difficult to keep up with the already challenging class. Its certainly doable but very challenging based on what Ive seen from 126 vs 55.

<md>You absolutely do not need to know poisson process and markov chains going into 126 as all of this material is taught from the ground up. The first third of the course is review of material from CS 70</md>

history.content: I know that the prereq for EECS 126 is officially CS70. I'm interested in taking the class, but have taken Math 55, not CS70 - would the probability in math 55 be a good background for EECS 126/does anyone have experience with this?
